#> 1: ÁRPÁD GÖNCZ, President of the Republic of Hungary (from the podium): Dear Parliament! Good day! I welcome you, our invited guests, all citizens of the country and all those who are watching the inaugural session of the National Assembly from here and beyond. I am opening the inaugural session of the National Assembly. (The sounds of the music become louder, those in the hall stand up and sing the National Anthem together.) Dear House! Dear friends! I respectfully greet you, the freely and democratically elected representatives of the second Parliament of the new Hungarian Republic. First of all, let me state proudly - I think, in agreement with you - the indisputable fact that during the 1994 representative election, in terms of its cleanness and execution, it took place flawlessly and smoothly, the strength and maturity of our democracy, and the high participation rate of the two rounds of our people it proves his interest in his own fate, the determined intention and awareness of his political expression. For all of this, thanks go to all the voters, the leaders and candidate representatives of the parties that participated in the election, the leaders of the National Election Committee that conducted the election - by name, primarily Dr. Professor János Németh - and his members, the leaders and members of all local election committees, the National Electoral Office that prepares the elections - by name Dr. Mr. Zoltán Tóth and Dr. Mrs. Ilona Pálffy and their excellent colleagues - all the colleagues of the Ministry of the Interior and local governments who were part of the election work, as well as the many thousands of volunteer workers, without whose self-sacrificing cooperation we would hardly be sitting here today. And let me thank the appointed representatives of the six parliamentary parties for the series of negotiations that took place in a short time and required mutual goodwill and flexibility, with which today's session was prepared - with the professional help of the General Secretariat of the Parliament and the Office of the Parliament. This series of negotiations, I feel, foreshadows the goal-setting working style of the new Parliament, which is expected to be ready for cross-party cooperation. The National Assembly is our country's highest public law body, which is ultimately responsible for its legislative work to the people of the country and, let me add: the country's future. He does his work in front of the eyes and ears of the people, and what he does determines our everyday life. Its basis is the past, its test is the present, its judge is the future. The electorate forms an opinion about it every day, even if it formulates its collective verdict four years later, at another election. No one can doubt the legality of your work, but you have to fight for its recognition with your words and votes every day during debates. It is up to you how the citizens of the country, Hungarians and non-Hungarians, judge the functioning of our democracy. And not only the citizens of the country - the universal Hungarians, also our compatriots living outside our borders, who are connected to us not by a legal bond, but by the past, the common language and culture, the millions of threads of the community of destiny, their interest in existence. Please do not forget for a moment that the legislative task and responsibility of the National Assembly does not raise it above the country and society, but obliges it to serve it! The National Assembly as a whole and each of its members is an inseparable member of society, and even if it is constantly shaped by its work, it is also shaped along with it - and is also a reflection of it. And although the legislative work of the National Assembly is mostly embodied in a legal form, it is changed by human and economic relations in everyday life, from which it directly follows that the essential tool and true breeding ground of their daily work is the accurate knowledge of the naked social reality, which no ideology can replace. It is not my task to summarize the experiences of the previous Parliament's four-year work or even to try to allude to it. (10.10) I will not undertake to give an answer to the question that always arises: did the people of the country vote for something or against something. But this much, I think, I can safely say that he voted for the expected future, just as he also wants to see his future as certain and predictable, and as peaceful - and as soon as possible -, one that takes him forward in time and not backward, and that the from the past - from any kind of past - he is ready to incorporate as much into his future as will make it stronger socially and economically, and which is in line with his moral value judgment. Because his natural wisdom demands social justice, sane equality of opportunity - he doesn't expect miracles or fried pigeons. You can sense good intentions, true words, dialogue, a say in the fate of property, even more so public purity. And make sure that they recognize all of this - as well as their opponent - verbally, in writing, and on screen. My recent conversations with the leaders of the six parliamentary parties, the tough discussions and the outcome of the coalition negotiations have convinced me that both the parties of the future government coalition and the future opposition are aware of the country's problems, the - by no means easy - tasks ahead of us, and they judge them similarly. the order of importance of the tasks of the National Assembly, so they are ready for fruitful dialogue, constructive debate and cooperation. Finally, I ask for God's blessing on the work of the National Assembly. I wish from the bottom of my heart to all the members of the House that what you do as a representative of the national assembly will benefit our country even if measured by the standards of your own conscience. (Applause.) Dear Parliament! I announce that in accordance with Section 2 (1) of the Rules of the House, 383 elected representatives have submitted their credentials by the time of the inaugural meeting. Dear Parliament! Pursuant to § 4 of the House Rules, until the election of the officers, the constituent meeting is chaired by the group president, and the four youngest representatives perform the secretarial tasks as the group registrars. As far as I know, the oldest representative is Dr. László Varga, representative of the Christian Democratic People's Party. (Applause.) The four youngest representatives: László Botka (MSZP), Tamás Deutsch (Fidesz), Péter Nahimi (MDF) and József Rimóczi (MSZP). I would like to ask the honorable Parliament if they are aware of anything else, are these data accurate? (No one applies.) Dear Parliament! To fulfill the duties of the co-chairman, Dr. I am asking representative László Varga, and the clerkship duties will be performed alternately by representatives László Botka and Tamás Deutsch, Péter Nahimi and József Rimóczi. I made the credentials available to the class president and the class registrars for the purpose of mandate examination. With this, I will hand over the leadership of the meeting to the co-chairman of the Parliament, and the two consecutive co-registrars will be Péter Nahimi and József Rimóczi. (Applause. - The President of the Republic, leaving the rostrum, shakes hands with Dr. László Varga, who is standing at the steps of the platform, and then takes his place according to the order of the meeting. - The president of the quorum, the quorum clerks and the secretary general of the National Assembly take their place at the presidential rostrum.)
