#> 1: Dr. LÁSZLÓ VARGA, co-speaker of the Parliamentary Assembly, henceforth president (stand and deliver his speech): Mr. President! Dear Parliament! I gratefully accept the seniority due to my years, but please don't take it as bias that - as a legacy to my trans-Danubian parents, who farmed a few acres when I was young, and lived on a tight budget: my mother, Anna Tóth, born in Egyházaskesző, my father, Géza Varga, born in Csorna, and by the grace of the Almighty - now , today I feel like a registrar. Forty-seven years ago, I sat on the right side of the National Assembly as a representative of the Democratic People's Party, the legal predecessor of today's Christian Democratic People's Party. In the second post-war election campaign in 1947, the Democratic People's Party emerged victorious, with sixty-two representatives, based on clear votes. Although we were the largest party in the country, we could not think of forming a government because of the occupation: we fought in the opposition so that citizens could exercise their fundamental rights without fear and freely, that our culture would be strengthened, that the creative individual should be the engine of our economic life; we protected the fruits of labor, private property - adding that every income includes social justice, which ensures the decent life and human dignity of workers -; furthermore, that the education of the youth should be based on knowledge, while their education should be based on the national spirit and Christian values. We could not achieve our goal because of the occupation, and as the repression in the country intensified, the anxiety of the citizens increased, and then the moment came when we were already afraid, I was afraid. It was a cruel feeling to realize that life ends where fear begins: there is only existence. And we focused all our thoughts and nerves on getting rid of the life-sapping feeling of fear. Poverty is an undesirable state, but in the course of history immortal works have been born in deprivation - never in fear, because terror kills all creative forces. The source of fear is arbitrariness and oppression, against which our people move almost every hundred years in its history. (10.20) I somewhat boldly list the XIII. the Golden Bull era of the 19th century, when the ruling orders protested against the arbitrariness of the king, later the uprisings of Antal Nagy Budai, György Dózsa, Ferenc Tokaji, then the freedom struggles of Rákóczi and Kossuth, just like in '56, the struggles against arbitrariness and oppression. The past and mentioned uprisings and freedom struggles have apparently failed. In reality, no, because every noble, selfless, sacrificial act will bear fruit sooner or later, and it will turn green even on the rock. Without Kossuth's struggle for freedom, there is no compromise, just as in 1956 he decisively contributed to the collapse of the communist system, but at the same time the whole world bowed down to Hungarianness and we regained our national respect. I pay tribute to all the legislators of 1947 who fought for our nation, such as István Barankovics, secretary general of the Democratic People's Party, dr. To Sándor Eckhardt, university professor, dr. Ferenc Mateovics, who is suffering from a terminal illness today; He spent 19 and a half years in prison for his principles, and when I asked him how he felt about those who caused his suffering, he replied: "Repent of your mistakes and sins and love your neighbors!" All I add to this behavior is that I respectfully bow my head before Paul, who became a Saul, I turn away from Sauls who speak Paul and I abhor Sauls who live in hatred and revenge. I also remember Zoltán Pfeiffer, the president of the Hungarian Independence Party, Imre Kovács, the author of "The Silent Revolution", Anna Kéthly, a social democrat from the coalition government, who as the vice-president of the National Assembly, bravely and boldly defended the opposition's freedom of speech. I think with grace of Imre Nagy, the Speaker of the National Assembly, whose opening speech was celebrated much more enthusiastically in the opposition than his own party. We felt his Hungarianness, the love of his people. He paid for it with his life. I think with gratitude of all those who during our 1100-year history sacrificed their freedom and their lives for our nation and those who during the last 40 years of occupation - on any side - and who made it possible with their work during the four years that we are here today, in an independent and free country to work for our nation. I respectfully remember the present Monsignor Béla Varga, the former president of the National Assembly, whose whole life was work for his people. (Prolonged applause. - Béla Varga stands up to thank the applause.) We must democratically accept the results of the 1994 elections, but at least acknowledge them. At the same time, the newly formed Government must also accept, or at least acknowledge, that power belongs to the people and that the Government's only task is to serve the people. Citizens' trust can only be enjoyed by those who preserve the independence of our country, ensure the exercise of the people's fundamental rights and the enforcement of social justice, increase knowledge, support education with a national spirit, and the educational and educational work of the historic churches. And last but not least, during this period of the National Assembly, during the four years, we will build the stronghold of our culture, the National Theatre, or at least start building it. Our democracy is not strengthened by the power of the Government, but when citizens exercise their rights not only in elections and through their representatives, but also in social, advocacy, cultural and other associations. Without it, all governments are prone to arbitrariness. President! Dear Parliament! Our people yearn for security, internal peace, and an improvement in our economic situation, and they rightly demand selfless and sacrificial work from all representatives. Since no party has a panacea to solve all difficulties, we must strive to reach an agreement on issues of public interest. The security of our country is not currently guaranteed by international treaties, and although we are not threatened by external threats, due to the almost never-ending cruel civil war in the former Yugoslavia - and because the forces of power in the former Soviet Union have not yet been clarified - it is necessary that even the Western European Through the Union or rather from NATO, we should get security so that we are not alone in case of danger. Our common cause is also the situation of minorities living outside our borders. We are the same in their history, language, and culture, so their fate is ours. I think we agree that it is the duty of all of us in international documents, such as the United Nations General Assembly l992. in its decision of December 18, to fight together for the rights granted to national minorities. Anyone who listens to this question will be hit by Babits' biblical judgment: "He who is silent is an accomplice among sinners." The path of our economic improvement and development is marked by the European Union, of which there are still twelve today, but soon the neighboring Austria and three other countries will join, which are often different in their history, language and interests, but by preserving their independence - and making sacrifices - the free man based on their business and production, they live in peace, democracy and satisfactory economic conditions. The average annual income of citizens of the European Union is more than HUF one million. Our country is an associate member of the European Union and we are moving towards full membership, so we are also guided by the principles and results that promoted the development of the members of the European Union. These prove that the state is not a good farmer. It is arbitrary, bureaucratic, slow and lacking in ideas. Keeping in mind the looming nationalization of the socialist system, we still have to strive for the state to hand over everything it can to the entrepreneurial citizen and to keep only what is necessary and not the other way around. In economic life, unlimited liberalism, the excesses and greed of the individual should be limited by social justice, which is more than social security, led by proportional and fair taxation. A country is not rich where there are many millionaires - even if there are some - but where there are no destitutes and few unemployed. Villas and palaces may be built, but the citizens of that country are contented and cheerful, where everyone has their own home, and young married people do not have to wait for years to spend the most beautiful period of their lives in their home. In our colorful and rich language, home means not only the apartment, but also the homeland. Based on what has been said, I believe that in a young democracy, the voters do not want to listen to unnecessary battles of words, nor do they want to see the empty fight between the Government and the opposition, but rather who does more for our people. For this purpose, it would be correct if the Government accepted all the proposals of the opposition that serve the public good, but at the same time the opposition should not protest against the Government's legislative proposal, the implementation of which is in the public interest. We are all here because of the people's trust. Trust is the most beautiful gift of life, which we are only worthy of if we serve our nation selflessly and sacrificially. Let there be no one among us who obtains a financial advantage from his position as a representative! If there is such a thing, let's get rid of it, because the voters want our work to benefit the country and not the representative! In this spirit - with my wife's consent - I will use my representative's salary for the construction costs of the National Theater and to help the needy. (Applause. - Continuous noise.) One of the conditions for the country's peace is that the non-armed powerhouse of our time, the electronic news service, should not serve the government or the opposition, but should inform the citizens objectively, fairly and ethically. This is the source of healthy public spirit - which is the spiritual current circulating between the Government and the people. (10.30) I believe that we also agree that we fight against all extremism. The strength of the extremes is that they preach attractive truths, but the goal is not to realize them, but to gain power. When they come to power, they are silent about the truths, and the arbitrariness of the legal guardian remains. I am convinced that all members of the National Assembly agree with me that there will be no reorganization in our country; but I will add that it cannot be, because the events that took place in the former socialist countries prove that development has passed through the outdated political system of communism, its extinguished idea will not be rekindled, and its economic system, which has fallen into the abyss, will not recover. President! Dear Parliament! The eyes of the citizens of our country are on us, the Hungarian minorities outside the borders, as well as our compatriots living in emigration and making many sacrifices for our nation, as well as European and overseas governments, are also watching our activities. It is our duty to protect the reputation of our country abroad, and at home to fight our opposites in a noble struggle, and the winner should not be a person, a party, the Government or the opposition, but our beloved country. Finally, allow me to close this very rare occasion with a personal confession. The struggles, glory and defeats of our history: my textbook. I happily and abundantly draw from our culture, which is contemporary with Christianity. Our beautiful language is the only written and spoken expression of my thoughts; in my difficulty, my frailty, my downfall, Christianity remained my guide. I belong to this nation, I am from the people, I live among the people and I work for the people. Nazism put me in prison, Communism drove me away, freedom brought me back. I thank the heavens and all my loyal compatriots that I can finish my public work where I started, at home. Thanks. (Prolonged applause.) Dear Parliament! Paragraph (5) of § 20 of the Constitution, as well as LV. 1990 on the legal status of representatives of the National Assembly. the law provides for conflicts of interest related to the office of representative. The representative group of the six parliamentary parties - if they allow me, I won't use the word faction because I don't like it - agreed that at the inaugural meeting we should present the list of representatives who have a conflict of interest, as well as the list of those who have eliminated the conflict of interest in the meantime. I would like to ask my representative, the age registrar, to introduce the list. Contents Previous Next Start Homepage
